# Playbook: oauth-prod-wiring

> Add the production callback URL and JS origin to an existing OAuth
> client so social login works behind the public domain, then verify the
> end-to-end login. Generic template — replace the `{{PLACEHOLDERS}}`.

## When to use

- The app already uses an OAuth provider (e.g. Google) that worked on
  `http://localhost:3000` in dev.
- The app is now reachable at its public domain via the tunnel.

## Parameters

| Name | Example | Resolved from |
|---|---|---|
| `{{DOMAIN}}` | `t0t0m0ndlale.online` | registered domain |
| `{{PROVIDER}}` | `google` | auth provider |
| `{{CALLBACK_PATH}}` | `/api/auth/callback/google` | framework (Auth.js) |

## Pre-flight checks (do these first, do not skip)

1. `https://{{DOMAIN}}` serves the app (tunnel Healthy).
2. The VM env has `AUTH_URL=https://{{DOMAIN}}` (matches the domain
   exactly — scheme + host, no trailing slash).
3. You can edit the OAuth client (e.g. Google Cloud Console >
   Credentials > the existing Web client).

## Steps

### 1. Add the production redirect URI

In the OAuth client's **Authorized redirect URIs**, add:

```
https://{{DOMAIN}}{{CALLBACK_PATH}}
```

Keep the existing `http://localhost:3000{{CALLBACK_PATH}}` for dev.

### 2. Add the production JS origin

In **Authorized JavaScript origins**, add:

```
https://{{DOMAIN}}
```

### 3. Save and wait

Google can take a few minutes to propagate client changes.

## Verify

- Open `https://{{DOMAIN}}`, click sign in with `{{PROVIDER}}`, complete
  the consent, and land back authenticated (the callback resolves).
- A non-allowlisted account is rejected by the app's own gate (if one
  exists), not by an OAuth error — that confirms authn vs authz separation.
- Session cookie is set on `{{DOMAIN}}`, login persists across reloads.

## Common pitfalls

- **`redirect_uri_mismatch`**: the URI must match **exactly**, including
  scheme and no trailing slash. `AUTH_URL` must equal the public origin
  or the framework builds the wrong callback.
- **Behind a proxy/tunnel host mismatch**: ensure the app trusts the
  forwarded host (`AUTH_URL` pin handles this for Auth.js) so it does not
  infer an internal host.
- **Editing the wrong client**: dev and prod often share one client; add
  URIs, do not replace the dev ones.

## What this playbook does NOT do

- Does **not** create the OAuth client or consent screen (one-time dev
  setup).
- Does **not** manage the app's own authorization/allowlist logic.
